{
  "text": "In particular, the displacement\u00fb 2 on \u2126 c is uniquely determined and may be computed from\u00fb| \u2202\u2126 +v with the help of layer potentials. Due to the lack of convexity of W , neither\u00fb nor \u2207\u00fb needs to be unique. However, Lemma 2.1 allows to identify subsets of \u2126, on which these quantities are well-defined. Proof. The proof closely follows the arguments of [CITATION_1] , Theorem 3. a) Let (\u00fb 1 ,v 1 ), (\u00fb 2 ,v 2 ) \u2208 A be two minimizers, and consider w =\u00fb 2 \u2212\u00fb 1 . Because P\u2207\u00fb 1 = P\u2207\u00fb 2 , \u2207w is parallel to A almost everywhere. It is easy to see that, therefore, w may be modified on a set of measure zero to yield an absolutely continuous function which is locally constant along the hyperplanes perpendicular to A. With w| \u0393t being 0 by Lemma 2.1, w also has to vanish on almost every hyperplane hitting \u0393 t . b) is a consequence of P\u2207\u00fb 1 = P\u2207\u00fb 2 , DW * * (\u2207\u00fb 1 ) = DW * * (\u2207\u00fb 2 ) and (4):",
